**20. Type Safety First**

TypeScript strict mode is non-negotiable. Every file must compile with zero errors.

**Type Safety Rules:**
- ✅ NEVER use `any` for user input (security risk)
- ✅ Define interfaces for all data structures
- ✅ Use discriminated unions for state machines
- ✅ Prefer `unknown` over `any` when type is truly unknown
- ✅ Add JSDoc comments for complex types

**Example - BAD:**
```typescript
const data: any = userInput; // DANGEROUS!
data.anything.works.here; // No type checking
```

**Example - GOOD:**
```typescript
interface UserInput {
  name: string;
  age: number;
}

const data: UserInput = validateInput(userInput);
data.name; // ✅ Type safe
data.unknown; // ❌ Compile error
```

**Before Committing:**
- Run `npm run type-check`
- Fix ALL errors (no suppressions)
- No `@ts-ignore` or `@ts-nocheck`
```

